<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Indian Classical & Folk Dances</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        .container {
            max-width: 900px;
            margin: auto;
            background: white;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 10px;
            box-shadow: 0px 0px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
            color: #892626;
        }
        .dance-section {
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        .dance-section:nth-child(even) {
            flex-direction: row-reverse;
        }
        .text {
            width: 50%;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        .video {
            width: 50%;
        }
        iframe {
            width: 100%;
            height: 250px;
            border-radius: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Indian Classical & Folk Dances</h1>

        <div class="dance-section">
            <div class="text">
                <h2>Bharatanatyam</h2>
                <p>Bharatanatyam is one of the oldest classical dance forms from Tamil Nadu. It is known for its graceful expressions, intricate footwork, and spiritual storytelling. Originally performed in temples, it embodies devotion and discipline.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="video">
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/JWhA3ldZcyY" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="dance-section">
            <div class="text">
                <h2>Kathak</h2>
                <p>Kathak, originating from North India, is a storytelling dance that combines rhythmic foot movements with graceful spins. It has both Hindu and Persian influences, showcasing intricate gestures and mesmerizing expressions.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="video">
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/UBYqv21c0Yk" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="dance-section">
            <div class="text">
                <h2>Kathakali</h2>
                <p>Kathakali from Kerala is a dramatic dance form characterized by elaborate makeup, colorful costumes, and powerful expressions. It narrates mythological stories through intense facial expressions and hand gestures.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="video">
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/Tl3UKV1z9lM" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="dance-section">
            <div class="text">
                <h2>Odissi</h2>
                <p>Odissi, originating from Odisha, is a fluid and graceful dance form often inspired by temple sculptures. It emphasizes movements of the torso and expressions, narrating devotional themes dedicated to Lord Jagannath.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="video">
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/LUHrTwrC3wU" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="dance-section">
            <div class="text">
                <h2>Kuchipudi</h2>
                <p>Kuchipudi from Andhra Pradesh blends dance, drama, and music. It features expressive storytelling and swift foot movements. Unlike other classical forms, it often includes dialogues and singing by the performers.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="video">
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/sfgqTiILKd0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="dance-section">
            <div class="text">
                <h2>Mohiniyattam</h2>
                <p>Mohiniyattam is a classical dance from Kerala performed by women. It features slow, graceful movements and fluid expressions, often depicting themes of love and devotion with a focus on feminine grace.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="video">
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/m_avP6toESU" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="dance-section">
            <div class="text">
                <h2>Manipuri</h2>
                <p>Manipuri, from Manipur, is a soft and delicate dance form, often inspired by the stories of Lord Krishna and Radha. It features fluid hand gestures, gentle footwork, and unique cylindrical costumes.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="video">
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/HzqQjdCSmuY" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="dance-section">
            <div class="text">
                <h2>Sattriya</h2>
                <p>Sattriya, from Assam, is a dance-drama tradition that originated in Vaishnavite monasteries. It combines storytelling, music, and rhythmic movements, depicting mythological themes with great devotion.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="video">
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/YJ15-lRx_dA" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="dance-section">
            <div class="text">
                <h2>Bhangra</h2>
                <p>Bhangra, a vibrant folk dance from Punjab, is energetic and joyous, performed during harvest festivals and celebrations. It includes lively jumps, powerful beats, and dynamic movements.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="video">
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/tZerERjfDKY" allowfullscreen></iframe>            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="dance-section">
            <div class="text">
                <h2>Garba</h2>
                <p>Garba, a traditional folk dance from Gujarat, is performed during Navratri. Dancers move in circular formations to rhythmic beats, celebrating devotion, joy, and unity.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="video">
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/1NOwfJgBHUE" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
